      <hedline>
        <hl1>Frozen Switches</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>I Milton Karabell letter on Matthew L Wald's May 21 travel article praises Amtrak for installing modern safety devices but questions why switches that do not freeze on cold days are not used; Amtrak spokesman Stephen Taubenkibel responds (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor: I was pleased to see that Amtrak is installing modern safety devices in ''Faster Amtrak Trains, Fancier Safeguards'' by Matthew L. Wald (May 21).</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor: I was pleased to see that Amtrak is installing modern safety devices in ''Faster Amtrak Trains, Fancier Safeguards'' by Matthew L. Wald (May 21).</p>
        <p>I would be happy if after 150 years of railroading they could come up with a switch that doesn't freeze on cold days. When the switches freeze, as they do almost every winter, the speed of the stopped trains is moot!</p>
        <p>I. MILTON KARABELL  Philadelphia</p>
        <p>Stephen Taubenkibel, an Amtrak spokesman, responds: In the Northeast Corridor, between Washington and Boston, we have switch heaters. Most of them are turned on from a center in Philadelphia if we know there will be heavy ice or severe weather.</p>
      </block>
